## Month 3: Learn RAG Properly

**Goal:** Build systems that let LLMs answer questions from your documents — not just from their training data. Produce answers that are grounded, accurate, and citable.

RAG is the most in-demand practical skill in AI engineering right now. Almost every real enterprise AI use case is built on it.

---

### 1. Embeddings

A text embedding is text projected into a high-dimensional vector space. Text that is semantically similar ends up close together in that space — which is what makes similarity search possible.

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Stack Overflow Blog: An Intuitive Introduction to Text Embeddings | [Link](https://stackoverflow.blog/2023/11/09/an-intuitive-introduction-to-text-embeddings/) |
| Google ML Crash Course: Embeddings | [Link](https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/embeddings) |
| HuggingFace: Getting Started With Embeddings | [Link](https://huggingface.co/blog/getting-started-with-embeddings) |
| OpenAI Embeddings Guide | [Link](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/embeddings) |

**Practice:** Take 20 sentences, embed them, and write a simple nearest-neighbor search that returns the 3 most similar to a query. This is RAG in miniature.

---

### 2. Chunking

Your documents are too large to embed as a whole. Chunking breaks them into smaller pieces before embedding. **How you chunk directly affects your system's ability to find relevant information.**

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Weaviate: Chunking Strategies for RAG | [Link](https://weaviate.io/blog/chunking-strategies-for-rag) |
| Unstructured: Chunking for RAG Best Practices | [Link](https://unstructured.io/blog/chunking-for-rag-best-practices) |
| LangChain Text Splitters Docs | [Link](https://python.langchain.com/docs/concepts/text_splitters/) |

> **Beginner tip:** Start with `RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter` from LangChain with `chunk_size=500` and `chunk_overlap=50`. A good starting point is ~250 tokens with 10-20% overlap between chunks.

**Core trade-off:** Chunks too large → lose retrieval precision. Chunks too small → lose context.

---

### 3. Vector Databases

Once you have embeddings, you need somewhere to store and search them efficiently.

| Database | Best For | Link |
|---|---|---|
| Chroma | Local prototyping, fast setup | [Link](https://docs.trychroma.com/) |
| Pinecone | Managed turnkey scale | [Link](https://www.pinecone.io/learn/) |
| Qdrant | Open-source, advanced filtering, self-hosting | [Link](https://qdrant.tech/documentation/) |
| pgvector | Already on PostgreSQL, no new infrastructure | [Link](https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector) |

**Practice project:** Index 50-100 pages from any public documentation into Chroma with metadata (source URL, section title). Write a query function that retrieves the 5 most relevant chunks for any question.

---

### 4. Metadata Filtering

Raw similarity search alone isn't enough. Metadata filtering lets you constrain retrieval to a relevant subset — by date, source, document type, user, category, or any other attribute.

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Pinecone: Metadata Filtering Guide | [Link](https://docs.pinecone.io/guides/data/filter-with-metadata) |
| LlamaIndex: Metadata Filters Guide | [Link](https://docs.llamaindex.ai/en/stable/module_guides/querying/node_postprocessors/node_postprocessors/) |

> **What makes the difference:** Tagging every chunk at ingestion time (source filename, page number, section, date, category) so users can ask "only show results from Q4 reports."

---

### 5. Reranking

After first-stage retrieval, a reranker re-scores results based on true contextual relevance — not just vector proximity. The result is dramatically better retrieval quality with only a modest latency cost.

**Pattern:** Embed and search (fast, approximate) → rerank top-k (slower, more accurate).

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Cohere Reranking Docs | [Link](https://docs.cohere.com/docs/reranking-with-cohere) |
| LangChain: Cohere Reranker Integration | [Link](https://python.langchain.com/docs/integrations/retrievers/cohere-reranker/) |

---

### 6. Retrieval Quality Issues

Most RAG failures aren't model failures — they're retrieval failures.

| Issue | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Semantic drift | Query embedding doesn't match chunk embedding | Query rewriting or HyDE |
| Chunk boundary problems | Relevant info split across two chunks | Increase overlap or use semantic chunking |
| Missing metadata context | Wrong document/date retrieved | Use metadata filtering |
| Top-k too small | Right chunk not in top 5 | Increase `top_k`, reduce after reranking |

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| LangChain: Query Transformations | [Link](https://python.langchain.com/docs/how_to/#query-analysis) |
| Pinecone: Improving Retrieval Quality | [Link](https://www.pinecone.io/learn/retrieval-augmented-generation/#retrieval-quality) |

---

### 7. Hallucination Reduction

RAG dramatically reduces hallucinations vs a vanilla LLM — but doesn't eliminate them. By supplying retrieved facts at runtime, RAG anchors responses to real sources.

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Zep: Reducing LLM Hallucinations – A Developer's Guide | [Link](https://www.getzep.com/ai-agents/reducing-llm-hallucinations/) |
| Voiceflow: 5 Ways to Reduce LLM Hallucinations | [Link](https://www.voiceflow.com/blog/prevent-llm-hallucinations) |

**Key strategy:** Prompt the model to answer only from provided context and say "I don't know" when the answer isn't there.

---

### 8. Citations and Grounding

A grounded RAG system doesn't just answer — it tells you where the answer came from. This is critical for user trust and debugging.

| Resource | Link |
|---|---|
| Anthropic: Giving Claude Sources | [Link](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/citations) |
| LangChain: RAG with Sources | [Link](https://python.langchain.com/docs/how_to/qa_sources/) |

